<h1>@HI{{nasai}}</h1>

<h2> Formation </h2>

<ol>
<li> @Vmasustem{{}}<strong>@HI{{nasai}}</strong>
</ol>

<h2> Definition </h2>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{nasai}}</strong> is used as a polite imperative by superiors to their inferiors. It is commonly used by parents to their children 
or by teachers to their pupils.
</p>

<h2> Examples </h2>

<ol>
<li>
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{mottotakusann@KJ{{eat}}be<strong>nasai</strong>.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Eat more.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<li>
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{play}}nanaide@KJ{{exertion^study}}shinasai.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Don't play. Study!
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</ol>

<h2> Notes </h2>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{nasai}}</strong> is the irregular imperative form of the honorific verb @HI{{nasaru}}.
</p>

<p>
An inferior should not use this form to a superior; instead <a href="grammar-te-kudasai.html">@HI{{kudasai}}</a> should be used.
</p>

